    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>The most famous Enginers of this day, In Millan, &amp; in Noriberg. Millan lernid of Cardan, or perhaps
                    Bombarders, Canoners, harnes, swords, targets, [etc.]</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Girolamo Cardano"/>
                    <location name="Milan"/>
                    <location name="Nuremberg"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>Noua Italoru[m], et Hisparnoum Stratagemata, adiuncta Frontino; mera Imitatio, Frontini, et Polya[e]ni.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Frontinus"/>
                    <person name="Polyaenus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The new strategies of the Italians and the Spanish, belonging to Frontinus. A mere imitation of Frontinus and Polyaenus. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>scit&egrave;</marginalia_text> <!--Underneat 'Frontino'-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Knowingly.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary" anchor_text="Loue hath no leaden heles">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Looue is not leaden heelid[.]</marginalia_text> <!--JG: Unsure, another letter after 'heelid'?-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Knowingly.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>In Frontino, plus Romanoru[m] Strategematu[m]; in Polya[e]no, plus Graecoru[m], et Barbarorum.
                    Frontino sola fere polemica: Polya[e]no, etia[m] techna[e] Oeconomica[e], Politica[e], Tyrannica[e].
                    Pauca[e] in vtroq[ue] mechanica[e].</marginalia_text> 
                    <person name="Frontinus"/>
                    <person name="Polyaenus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>In Frontinus, there are more Roman strategies; in Polyaenus, there are more Greek and barbarian strategies.
                In Frontinus, there are only military [devices]. In Polyaenus, there are also economic, political, and tyrannical devices. 
            In both books, there are few things about engineering.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
                    <marginalia_text>Tria, aut quatuor propria, et inaudita Strategemata; digna sexcentis scriptis, et vsitatis. 
                        Politicu[m], et polymechanicum Ingeniu[m], miras Inuentiones excogitat.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Inopinata, et incredibilia valet plurimu[m].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Three or four particular and novel strategies; worthy of 600 texts and common usage. <!--JG: Unsure abt best translation of usitatis-->
          Political and polymechanic devices come up with wonderful inventions. The unforeseen and the extraordinary is worth much.
            </translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="so is al labour light, where loue hyreth the workeman">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>All labo[r] light, where looue hyreth [the] workman.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Verus Amor nullum nouit habere modum.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Sextus Propertius" book_title="Elegies"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>True love knows to have no limit.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
